Mission instructions

Recursion is a powerful tool in computer science, enabling elegant solutions to complex problems by breaking them down into simpler subproblems. In this exercise, you will explore various types of problems that can be effectively solved using recursion. 

In this exercise, loops may be used **only** for displaying the menu, reading user input, and printing output. These parts are already implemented in the `ex4.c` file in the git repository.  
Therefore, you must **not** use loops in your own code: **all problem solutions must be done *only* by using recursion.**

The file ex4.c is already created and you can see it here: [https://github.com/CSI-BIU/ex](https://github.com/CSI-BIU/ex4)4  
Just fork the repository and work on the file on your computer.

The file already includes the code that displays the main menu, receives input from the user, and prints the output (for all tasks except Tasks 1 and 2, where input and output handling is part of your solution).

Each task has a function named in the format `task{X}{TaskName}`. This function is responsible for managing the user interaction — reading input and printing output. Inside it, you will find a call to another empty function named `task{X}{TaskName}Implementation`. This second function receives the relevant input as parameters and is expected to return the computed result. Your recursive solution should be implemented inside this function.  
**You are not allowed to change the signatures of the given functions.**

**Note that your recursive function does not have to use the exact signature of the provided function. You may define any number of helper functions, with whatever parameters you find appropriate, in order to simplify your recursive logic.**

**Example:**  
In Task 2, which checks whether a phrase is a palindrome, the provided code includes a function `task2CheckPalindrome` that reads the phrase length from the user and passes it to `task2CheckPalindromeImplementation`. You should implement your recursive solution inside `task2CheckPalindromeImplementation`.  
If your solution requires a helper function (for example, one that receives more parameters), you are free to create and use such a helper function as part of your solution. You are not obligated to implement the actual recursive functions with the given function signatures,

There are comments to help you inside the files, but the full explanation will be in this document.

For your convenience, the basic tests used by the submit system are also available in the git repository, under the tests folder.

**Before you start, know that:**  
Your program is allowed to run **at most** \- 60 seconds.  
Obviously, we won’t enter tests that are super long, but if the TA program works twice as fast as yours \- you may want to optimize your solutions.  
The submit will write for you how much time your program runned.  
If it’s more than the allowed for the basic solutions \- you may consider your grade 0\.  
Please notice \- you don’t know what the final input tests are, so \- you need to verify your program is running relatively fast, in the general case.

Full explanation:  
**Phrase Reversal**  
**![][image1]**  
You have been assigned to develop a feature for a new text-processing module that mirrors phrases for visual display. In this task, the program receives a phrase from the user and must output the same phrase in reverse order, as if reflected in a mirror.

**Problem Definition:**  
Your task is to write a recursive function that processes the input phrase one character at a time until it reaches the first newline character (`'\n'`), and then prints the reversed version of the phrase.

**User Interaction:**  
When the user selects this task from the menu, the program will display the following message (managed by the provided code):  
`Please insert phrase to reverse:`  
The user will then input a phrase. Your program should read the input up to the first newline character (`'\n'`) and print:  
`The reversed phrase is:\n`  
followed by the reversed phrase on a new line

**Implementation Details:**  
The code for this task should be implemented in the following function:  
`void task1ReversePhraseImplementation()`  
This function is responsible for handling the input, printing the `"The reversed phrase is:\n"` message, and displaying the reversed result.  
Spaces are considered regular characters and should not be ignored.  
**Note that there is no theoretical limitation on the length of the input.**

**Example input and output:**  
Input:  
Please insert phrase to reverse:  
loop  
Output:  
The reversed phrase is:  
pool

**Palindrome Check**

![][image2]

You are assigned to develop a feature for a text analyzer that identifies special phrases known as *palindromes* — phrases that read the same forward and backward. In this task, your program will determine whether a given phrase is a palindrome using recursion.

**Problem Definition:**  
Your task is to write a recursive function that determines whether a given phrase is a palindrome — meaning it reads the same forward and backward.

The program should first read the length of the phrase and then read the phrase itself, character by character.

Spaces are considered regular characters and should not be ignored.

**User Interaction:**  
When the user selects this task from the menu, the program should display the following message (managed by the provided code):  
`Please insert the phrase length:`  
The user will enter an integer indicating the number of characters in the word (including spaces).  
You may assume this number is non-negative (\>=0).  
Then, the program will display (managed by the provided code):  
`Please insert the phrase to check:`  
The user will enter the word, and the program will check whether it is a palindrome.  
You may assume that the phrase the user enters is exactly the specified length.  
Finally, the program should print one of the following messages, depending on the result (managed by the provided code):  
`The phrase is a palindrome.`  
or  
`The phrase is not a palindrome.`

**Implementation Details:**  
The code for this task should be implemented in the following function:  
`int task2CheckPalindromeImplementation(int length)`  
This function receives the length of the phrase as a parameter and is responsible for reading the phrase itself and determining whether it is a palindrome.  
The function should return 1 if the phrase is a palindrome and 0 if it is not.  
**Note that there is no theoretical limitation on the length of the input. The only limitation is on the highest value the parameter** `length` **can hold (MAX\_INT).**

**Example input and output:**  
**Example 1:**  
**Input:**  
Please insert the phrase length:  
15  
Please insert the phrase to check:  
step on no pets  
**Output:**  
The phrase is a palindrome.  
**Example 2:**  
**Input:**  
Please insert the phrase length:  
5  
Please insert the phrase to check:  
intro  
**Output:**  
The phrase is not a palindrome.

**Generate Sentences**  
Sentences can be created by combining different parts — a subject, a verb, and an object — much like assembling building blocks into meaningful expressions.  
In this task, you will create a small sentence generator. The user will provide three separate lists—subjects, verbs, and objects—and your program will produce all possible sentences formed by choosing one item from each list.

**Problem Definition:**  
Your task is to write a recursive function that, given three lists of strings (subjects, verbs, objects), generates every possible sentence of the form: \<subject\> \<verb\> \<object\>.  
Each list may contain multiple words or phrases (for example, “The student”, “The robot”, etc.). Your function should print the full set of sentences in a consistent, numbered order.

**User Interaction:**

When the user selects this task from the menu, the program will display the following messages (managed by the provided code):  
First, the program will ask for the number of subjects:  
`Please insert number of subjects:`  
The user will then enter the number of different subjects.  
Then, the program will ask the user to enter the list of subjects:  
`Please insert the list of subjects:`  
The user will enter each subject on a separate line. The program will display a running index before each input (e.g., `1.`, `2.`, …).  
Next, the program will handle the verbs in a similar way:  
`Please insert number of verbs:`  
The user will enter the number of different verbs.  
`Please insert the list of verbs:`  
The user will enter each verb on a separate line, again preceded by an index.  
Then, the program will handle the objects:  
`Please insert number of objects:`  
The user will enter the number of different objects.  
Then the program will ask the user to enter the list of objects:  
`Please insert the list of objects:`  
The user will enter each object on a separate line, preceded by an index.  
Finally, the program will generate and enumerate and print all possible sentences that can be created from the provided vocabulary:  
`List of Sentences:`  
`1. …`  
`2. …`  
`3. …`  
`…`

**Implementation Details:**  
The code for this task should be implemented in the following function:

`void task3GenerateSentencesImplementation(char subjects[][LONGEST_TERM+1], int subjectsCount, char verbs[][LONGEST_TERM+1], int verbsCount, char objects[][LONGEST_TERM+1], int objectsCount);`  
This function receives the three vocabulary lists it should use to generate the sentences:

* `subjects[][LONGEST_TERM+1]` – an array of strings representing the list of subjects.  
* `subjectsCount` –the number of subjects in the array.  
* `verbs[][LONGEST_TERM+1]` – an array of strings representing the list of verbs.  
* `verbsCount` –the number of verbs in the array.  
* `objects[][LONGEST_TERM+1]` – an array of strings representing the list of objects.  
* `objectsCount` –the number of objects in the array.

You may assume the following:

* The **maximum length of a single term** (in any of the lists) is **20 characters**.  
* The **longest sentence** you may be required to generate is therefore **62 characters** (including spaces).  
* The **maximum number of terms** in each list (subjects, verbs, and objects) is **10**.  
* Each list will contain **at least one term**.  
* The user provides **exactly** the number of terms specified.

To maintain consistency, sentences **must** be generated in the order in which the terms were entered:

1. Start with the **first subject**  
2. For that subject, go over all verbs in the order they were entered,  
3. For each (subject, verb) pair, go over all objects in the order they were entered.

Your implementation should use recursion to generate these combinations and print the resulting sentences with their running indices, as shown in the example.

**Example input and output:**  
**Input:**  
Please insert number of subjects:  
3  
Please insert the list of subjects:  
1\. The program  
2\. The compiler  
3\. The student  
Please insert number of verbs:  
2  
Please insert the list of verbs:  
1\. executes  
2\. debugs  
Please insert number of objects:  
1  
Please insert the list of objects**:**  
1\. the code   

**Output:**  
List of Sentences:  
1\. The program executes the code  
2\. The program debugs the code  
3\. The compiler executes the code  
4\. The compiler debugs the code  
5\. The student executes the code  
6\. The student debugs the code

**Zip Puzzle**

In the Zip Puzzle, the goal is to find a path that passes through every tile of a square grid exactly once, while visiting all numbered tiles in strict ascending order.

![][image3]

**Problem Definition:**  
Your task is to write a recursive program that, given a Zip Puzzle board, finds the path with the following properties:

* The path moves only between horizontally or vertically adjacent tiles (no diagonal moves).  
* Every tile in the grid is visited **exactly once**.  
* All numbered tiles (tiles with values \> 0\) are visited in **ascending numeric order** according to their values (for example,the tile with value `1` must be visited before the tile with value `2`, and so on, up to the highest tile value).

A solution is valid only if **all** these conditions are satisfied.

**User Interaction:**

In this part, you can assume the user will enter only valid input that structurally represents a valid NxN grid, contains at least one numbered tile, and has no duplicates. All numbered tiles are consecutively labeled, starting from 1\.  
All user interactions are managed by the provided code.

When the user selects this task,  the program will display the following messages:  
First, the user will be asked to enter the dimensions of the puzzle grid (all boards are square and have the same number of rows and columns):  
`Please enter the board size:`  
The user will then input one integer representing the number of rows in the board.  
You can assume the maximal grid size is 20×20.  
If the user enters an illegal grid size, the following error message will be displayed:  
`Invalid board size.`  
and the user will be returned to the main menu.  
Then, the user will be asked to provide to puzzle’s grid with the following message:  
`Please enter the grid:`  
The user will provide the grid layout (in this example we assumed the grid size is 6):  
`8   7   0   0   0   0`  
`0   1   0   0   5   6`  
`9   11  0   0   0   4`  
`0   10  0   0   2   3`  
`15  16  0   0   0   12`  
`0   0   0   0   14  13`

Each number represents a tile in the grid:

* 0 represents a **regular (empty) cell**.  
* Positive integers (1 to highest) represent **numbered tiles**.

The starting point for the path is the tile with value 1, and the target tile is the one with the highest value (in this example, 16).

For example, the input in the example represent the following puzzle:

![][image4]

The program will find a path that starts at tile number 1, finishes at the highest numbered tile, and visits all cells exactly once while visiting numbered tiles in ascending order.

If the program finds a valid path, it should display the solution in the following format:

`Solution:`  
`D L L L L L`   
`D R R D R U`   
`D R D D U L`   
`R U D R R U`   
`R X R R R D`   
`U L L L L L` 

Each character represents the move **from** that cell:

* **U** – move up  
* **D** – move down  
* **L** – move left  
* **R** – move right  
* **X** – marks the **last** tile in the path

For example, the solution in the example represents the following path:

![][image5]

Otherwise, it should print:  
`No solution exists.`

**Implementation Details:**

The code for this task should be implemented in the following function:  
`int task4SolveZipBoardImplementation(int grid[ZIP_MAX_GRID_SIZE][ZIP_MAX_GRID_SIZE], char solution[ZIP_MAX_GRID_SIZE][ZIP_MAX_GRID_SIZE], int size, int startR, int startC, int highest)`  
This function receives:

* `grid[ZIP_MAX_GRID_SIZE][ZIP_MAX_GRID_SIZE]` – a two-dimensional array representing the puzzle grid. Empty tiles are represented with 0, and numbered tiles by their integer values.  
* `solution[ZIP_MAX_GRID_SIZE][ZIP_MAX_GRID_SIZE]` – a two-dimensional array for storing the solution path.  
* `size` – the dimensions of the puzzle board (size × size).  
* `startR, startC` – the row and column indices of the starting position (the tile with the number 1).  
* `highest`– the value of the last tile to be visited (the highest numbered tile).

The function should:

* Search for a valid path that satisfies all puzzle rules.  
* Update the solution matrix to reflect the path (with the appropriate direction characters and X for the last tile),  
* Return 1 if a solution was found, and 0 otherwise.

You are **not** obligated to implement the actual recursive logic directly inside `task4SolveZipBoardImplementation`. You may define and use additional helper functions with any parameters you find appropriate, as long as `task4SolveZipBoardImplementation` uses them, correctly fills the `solution` matrix, and returns the appropriate result (`1` or `0`).

To ensure your solution is consistent with the school solution (and the automatic tests) please explore the possible paths in the following order: U→ D → L → R.

**Example Input and Output:**  
**Input:**  
Please enter the board size:  
`2`  
Please enter the grid:  
`0 1`  
`0 2`  
**Output:**  
Solution:  
D L   
R X

**Sudoku Solver**  
**![][image9]**

Sudoku is a popular number-placement puzzle played on a 9×9 grid, where the goal is to fill in the missing digits so that each row, column, and 3×3 box contains the numbers 1 through 9 exactly once. It appears daily in newspapers and apps around the world—and if you’ve never seen one before… Well, welcome to Earth.

While many people spend long minutes (or hours) wrestling with “expert” Sudoku boards, your task is to write a program that can solve the same puzzles in a tiny fraction of a second. Instead of trial-and-error with a pencil, your recursive algorithm will produce a valid completed board effortlessly.

**Problem Definition:**  
Your task is to write a recursive program that completes a partially filled Sudoku board. A valid Sudoku solution must satisfy all of the following rules:

* Each row must contain the digits 1–9 exactly once.  
* Each column must contain the digits 1–9 exactly once.  
* Each 3×3 sub-grid (also called a box) must contain the digits 1–9 exactly once.

Empty cells are represented by 0\. Your function should fill all empty cells in a way that satisfies all Sudoku constraints.  
 A solution is valid only if **all three** conditions are met.

**User Interaction:**

In this part, you may assume that the user enters only valid input that structurally represents a Sudoku board, and that all pre-numbered cells are legally placed, meaning no number appears more than once in any row, column, or box. This assumption does not, however, guarantee that a legal solution exists.

When the user selects this task from the menu, the program will display the following message (managed by the provided code):  
`Please enter the sudoku board:`  
The user will then input 9 lines, each containing 9 digits (0–9) representing the puzzle.

For example, the following input represents this puzzle:  
**![][image10]**

`0 9 3   1 0 5   6 4 0`  
`7 0 0   0 0 0   0 0 5`  
`5 0 1   2 0 9   3 0 7`

`2 0 0   0 0 0   0 0 3`  
`0 3 6   9 0 7   5 2 0`  
`9 0 0   0 0 0   0 0 1`

`3 0 2   4 0 8   1 0 9`  
`6 0 0   0 0 0   0 0 4`  
`0 4 7   3 0 2   8 5 0`

The program will search for a valid solution for the puzzle and will print it (using the `printSudoku` function):

`Solution found:`  
`+-------+-------+-------+`  
`| 8 9 3 | 1 7 5 | 6 4 2 |`   
`| 7 2 4 | 8 3 6 | 9 1 5 |`   
`| 5 6 1 | 2 4 9 | 3 8 7 |`   
`+-------+-------+-------+`  
`| 2 1 5 | 6 8 4 | 7 9 3 |`   
`| 4 3 6 | 9 1 7 | 5 2 8 |`   
`| 9 7 8 | 5 2 3 | 4 6 1 |`   
`+-------+-------+-------+`  
`| 3 5 2 | 4 6 8 | 1 7 9 |`   
`| 6 8 9 | 7 5 1 | 2 3 4 |`   
`| 1 4 7 | 3 9 2 | 8 5 6 |`   
`+-------+-------+-------+`

For example, the above solution represents this solution:  
![][image11]

If no solution could be found, the program will print:  
`No solution exists.`

**Implementation Details:**

The code for this task should be implemented in the following function:

`int task5SolveSudokuImplementation(int board[SUDOKU_SIZE][SUDOKU_SIZE]);`

* This function receives a 9×9 Sudoku board in which:  
  0 represents an empty cell,  
* Digits 1–9 represent fixed numbers that cannot be changed.

The function should:

* Use a **recursive** approach to fill all empty cells.  
* Return 1 if a valid solution is found (and update the board array accordingly),  
* Return 0 if the puzzle has no valid solution.

You are **not obligated** to implement the recursive logic directly inside `task5SolveSudokuImplementation`. You may define and use any helper functions you find appropriate, as long as the final board is updated correctly and the return value reflects whether a solution exists.

To ensure your solution is consistent with the school solution (and with the automatic tests), you must explore the possible solutions **from left to right and top to bottom**: start from the top-left cell of the board, proceed row by row, and for each empty cell try the possible values in **ascending order**.
